"Car Bee" Prevents Crashes
This time, Nissan was inspired by nature, specifically by bees, to advance the development of technologies to protect against accidents.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the bee flying pattern and thus prevents collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which is the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Center for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. Robot have developed in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhira Doie, General Director of Public Relations for Technology, Research and Brand Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four safety shield zones.
The task of the robot is to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions in vehicles of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the most important are complex bees of the eye, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
When creating this visual feature, the engineers proposed what they called the Laser Range Finder (Laser Range Finder).
It records obstacles up to a distance of two meters in a 180 degree circle before BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns it into a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics the bee's movement and immediately changes direction by turning the wheel to a right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference compared to any existing system is the fact that all moving maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited only to two dimensions and to the direction in which it is allowed to rotate its wheel, but not in an infinite number of directions and options as with bees.
In addition to speeding up and slowing down, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent a collision.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and behave according to this data.
It does not require the retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just two dozen kB of memory.
You may be surprised, but we’re not talking about gigs or megas.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology where Nissan predicts the use of serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS system of satellite navigation, which would lead the driver to the destination and avoid obstacles on the way.
