Morgan Stanley has announced that Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan’s largest bank, will spend nine billion dollars to raise 21% of its capital. The adoption of this report led to a significant decline in its stock market price.
A week after they revealed their preliminary deal, the two banks explained that MUFG intends to buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s common stock at a flat price of $25.25, representing a total payout of $3 billion.
The agreed price is 19 % lower than the carrying amount of securities as at 31 August.
MUFG is investing an additional $6 billion to acquire convertible securities, which will provide it with a 10% return and whose exchange rate is $31.25.
Morgan Stanley clarified that the entire operation will be carried out on the basis of the average unit price of $29, i.e. 28% below its current rate.
Morgan Stanley’s shares lost 6.79 percent and rose to $23.07 at around 17.00 Greenwich time.
“This strategic merger represents an important opportunity on the way to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to a banking holding status,” said John Mack, CEO of the group.
The new statute was adopted by Morgan Stanley last week, allowing him to diversify his activities, but at the same time it is placed under the supervision of the Federal Reserve Bank.
His merger with the MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest axis to take a far more cautious approach than before.
The terms presented on Monday show, among other things, that the deal has changed over the past few days: last Monday Morgan only announced that he was selling up to 20% of his shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“We thought a week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, the MUFG’s executive director, told reporters in Tokyo, “that our participation will consist solely of common actions.
However, given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and also cover up.”
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay 7% less for Morgan Stanley securities than their carrying amount.
And the operation will result in a 20% reduction in the profit from the share.
The agreement foresees that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares in a year if they are last named for a certain period of time at a price of 50 % exceeding the exchange rate, i.e. at approximately $ 47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital brought by MUFG will enable him to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen his balance sheet and increase his cash.
However, the group refused to provide detailed information on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After the MUFG investment, Morgan Stanley should boast about 15% of Tier One’s ability to pay, which is one of the best in the industry.
Morgan pointed out that since the end of August, he has "citly" reduced his balance.
